doc.line: "Issued when the navigation engine establishes the DBUS connection. Before this signal is emitted, the navigation engine is not guaranteed to receive any DBUS messages"

"This signal is issued when the navigation engine is about to close down, either before shutting down or restarting. No more DBUS messages will be processed after this point, including the ShutdownRequest signal."

"This signal is a response to the ShutdownRequest signal sent by the JCI environment. Naturally, ReadyToDie does not immediately follow the message ShutdownRequest: several seconds are needed before the navigation engine prepares to close appropriately."
"This signal is sent out periodically (1 second by default)"
"This signal is issued if NNG has finished validating the content"
This signal is issued whenever there seems to be a problem with the SD card
Informal description of the problem
NOT_NAVI (0): The sdcard inserted is not for navigation
INVALID_NAVI (1): The SD card looks like an SD card for navigation, (etc. file corruption).
MODIFIED_INVALID_NAVI (2): The SD card looks like an SD card for navigation that the user tampered with.
LICENSE_PROBLEM (3): The SD card looks like an SD card for navigation, but none of the licenses are valid.
RESTART_MAY_HELP (0): It is possible that restarting the software will solve the problem (with the same sd card)
RESTART_WONT_HELP (1): With this sd card, restart will not solve the problem.
RESTART_NOT_NEEDED (2): There is some minor problem with the sd card, but the navigation engine will survive.
"This signal indicates a serious problem on the internal flash disk. NNG will terminate, and there is no use restarting it."
Informal description of the problem

Mode = enum( TIME_AUTO (0), TIME_MANUAL (1) )
TimeStamp: The value of the monotonic system clock (millisecond precision) when the reply to GetTimeMode was sent out. Will be ignored on the receiving side if Mode is TIME_AUTO.

DispayedTime: The time that should be displayed (according to the user) when the reply to GetTimeMode was sent out. The first unsigned 16-bit value represents the year, then the following five bytes correspond to the month, day, hour, minute and second respectively. It will be ignored on the receiving side if Mode is TIME_AUTO.
This method is used to notify a running NNG system that the user changed the time mode (or the displayed time)
